 the history of studio libraries occurred during the mid to late 1940s, when changes in American culture and an industry-wide recession convinced the studios to employ their libraries as profit centers through the use of theatrical reissues. In the 1950s, intermediary distributors used the growing market of television to harness libraries aggressively as foundations for cross-media expansion, a trend that continues today. By the late 1960s, the television marketplace and the exploitation of film libraries became so lucrative that they prompted conglomerates to acquire the studios. The first book to discuss film libraries as an important and often underestimated part of Hollywood history, Hollywood Vault presents a fascinating trajectory that incorporates cultural, legal, and industrial history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMotion picture film collectionsxEconomic aspects. 0aMotion picture industryzUnited StatesxFinance. 0aMotion picture studioszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxDistribution. 7aART / Film & Video.2bisacsh  aamerican culture.  abusiness and industry.  acinema.  acontemporary digital marketplace.  across media expansion.  acultural studies.  afilm industry.  afilm libraries.  afilm.  afilmmaking.  afilms with sound.  ahistory of cinema.  ahistory.  ahollywood history.  ahollywood.  aindustrial history.  aindustry transformation.  alegal studies.  along term implications.  amovie industry.  anew markets.  aold films.  aremakes.  aretrospective.  asilent era of film.  astar system.  astudio libraries.  atechnology.  atelevision.  atheatrical reissues.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz9780520282636